{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183566/1930101601/0836.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD, THURSDAY, OCTOBER 16, 1930.\n19\nInquiry Into Laborers Providing\nLiquor for Foremen Is Ruled Out\nBy Mayor at Meeting of Council\nQuigley Bangs Gavel and\nSquelches Aid. Johnson\nPublic Works Board\nCalled. On to Provide\nPlan for Spending $100,\n000 On Streets.\nAngered by a resolution presented\nlo the common council last night by\nAldermen Johnson and Talk and\nCouncllmen Holmberg and Ohlson\nrequesting the board of public works\nto ascertain the truth of reports that\nlaborers have been obliged to pro\nvide liquor for foremen In order to\nretain their Jobs, Mayor Quigley\nspeedily ruled it out of order and\nbanged the gavel when Alderman\nJohnson attempted to speak on the\nsubject\nThe meeting was one of the live\nliest of the Quigley administration,\na number of matters coming In for\naction in the form of resolutions and\npetitions.\nConlon Attacks Johnson\nAlderman Johnson and others\npresented a resolution calling on the\nboard of public works to present a\nbudget of streets to be repaired\nwhen $100,000 Is available through\nan issue of notes to be voted on at\na special council meeting next Mon\nday. The resolution also stated that\nan -Inspection of the streets will be\nmade Saturday afternoon and urged\nthat all members take part In order\nto avail themselves of information\nof importance before voting on the\nexpenditure of the money.\nCouncilman Frank L. Conlon\nflayed Alderman Johnson and prais\ned the board of public works, de\nclaring that the board was deserving\nof the confidence of the council and\npolitics should be left out of city af\nfairs. He charged that the signers\nof the resolution were prompted by\npolitical motives, and Councilman\nSamuel Sablotsky charged that it\nwas an attempt to block Mayor\nQuigley's drive to provide work for\nthe unemployed. The mayor, he said,\nwas to be congratulated on his ef\nforts and should not be hampered.\nEddy-Glover boulevard in the sixth\nward. Is being put in passable con\ndition and Alderman Johnson and\nthe other signers of the resolution\nwere attempting to prevent its com\npletion, Councilman Sablotsky said.\nFalk Denies Charge of Politics\nAlderman Johnson replied that he\nwould not be so foolish as to at\ntempt to leave a street Job half fin\nished, and although he had confi\ndence in the board of public works\nhe saw no reason why council mem\nbers should not be sufficiently inter\nested in their work to make a tour\nof inspection. \"Either we can come\nup here and be rubber stamps or we\ncan look into these matters before\nwe vote to spend the city's money\"\nhe declared. Alderman Falk sup\nported him and added that there\nwas no ground for the charge that\npolitics entered into the matter. The\nresolution was adopted, as was an\nother presented by Councilman Gib\nney asking the board of public\nworks to inform the council month\nly as to the work done and the con\ntemplated program for the following\nmonth. Councilman Gibney said no\ncriticism was intended but he felt\nthat the council and the public\nworks board should work together\nand be closer to each other than\nthey have been.\nAlderman Johnson presented a\nresolution to have the seating ar\nrangement in the council chamber\nchanged to conform to the layout in\ntho old chamber, and a difference of\nopinion was immediately provoked.\nCouncilman Conlon wanted to know\nif Alderman Johnson was finding it\ndifficult to marshal his forces on the\nfloor because of the present ar\nrangement. Alderman Johnson re\nplied that some members whose\nseats were in the rear of the cham\nber had complained of inability to\nhear what was said in the front\nrows and he believed the old layout\nwas best.\nAlderman D. L. Kair moved to\ntable the resolution for one month\nfor consideration and Investigation,\nand Councilman Conlon amended to\ntable it indefinitely. The amend\nment was lost and the motion pre\nvailed. Would Correct Salary list\nCouncilman Hanes and Wllford\npresented a resolution calling on\nthe ordinance and salaries commit\ntees to act to correct the condition\ncaused by carrying Deputy Building\nInspector Thomas B. Fay and Miss\nMae Butler, clerk in the building\ndepartment office, as temporary em\nployes. The resolution mentioned\nthat Fay's salary, which he receives\nmonthly from the incidental ac\ncount, was slashed at the opening\nof the present administration and\nslightly increased since then, and\nthe signers felt that it was not ad\nvisable to handle the office in that\nmanner.\nThe resolution was referred as re\nquested and when the ordinance and\nsalaries committee consider it, ac\ntion may be taken to place the two\nemployes on the regular salary list\nand pay them out of the salary ap\npropriation. A petition presented by Council\nman Sablotsky requesting the school\nboard to consider the practicability\nof abandoning the portable building\nin use at the Stanley school, was Tf-\nLOANS ON TIME\nIt is as businesslike to\nbuy money on time as it\nit to buy anything clsa\nyou need. Cash quickly,\nconfidentially up to $300.\nRepay $1.00 per week it\nnecessary. Hates only\n3 'a per month.\nMutual Industrial\nService\n111 Main Ovr Ashler's\nPhone 1751 Daily 0-6:30,\nSaturday 9-1, 1-0\nferred to the school board.\nA petition from the Holy eross\nRoman Catholic church corporation\nfor rebatement of a sewer assess\nment on Biruta street was referred\nto the corporation counsel, the\nmayor and aldermen. The petition\ners set forth that the property Is ex\nempt from assessments on account\nof Its use for church purposes.\nAdam Mlerzejewskl of 148 Farm\nir.gton avenue presented a claim for\n$3070.90 'damage to his property,\nalleging that the city installed a\ncatch basin but failed to connect it\nwith the storm water sewer, with\nthe result that floods occurred on\nhis property. It was referred to the\nbeard of public works.\nBuell Street Curbs and Walks\nAldermen Falk and Johnson\nspoke on a petition presented by\nBuell street residents to have side\nwalks and curbs installed. The\nwork was ordered done by October\n1 and the majority of the property\nowners have complied, the aldermen\nsaid. \"If the poor man can afford\nit, the rich man can, too,\" Alder\nman Johnson asserted. The matter\nwas referred to the board of public\nworks.\nMrs. Mary Curtin petitioned for a\nchange in zone of property on West\nMain street between High and Cedar\nstreets and the matter was referred\nto the board of adjustment to hold\na hearing. The section Is zoned for\nresidential purposes and the peti\ntioner wants It changed to a busi\nness zone.\nAbraham Kolodney petitioned for\na change in zone affecting property\nat. Stanley and Allen streets. It was\nlikewise referred to the board of ad\njustment for a hearing. The peti\ntioners want the section zoned for\nbusiness, which aroused strong op\nposition when attempted some time\nago.\nAlderman Johnson presented a\nresolution calling on the ordinance\ncommittee to hold a hearing on the\nproposed change in zone of property\non West Main street The board of\nadjustment has already recommend\ned that it be changed to a business\nzone, on petition Of Fred Beloin,\nowner of property at Sherman\nCourt and West Main street, but\nsurrounding property owners have\nremonstrated against the proposed\nuse of the property for gasoline fill\ning station purposes. The resolution\nwas adopted and a public hearing\nwill be given shortly.\nThe petition of Paul and Emma\nReale for a change of zone to per\nmit the use of property at Arch and\nMonroe streets as a miniature golf\ncourse was referred to the board of\nadjustment for a hearing.\nWants Zoning Ordinance Clarified\nAlderman Nair observed that it\nwas time the zoning ordinance was\nclarified to state definitely whether\nthe board of adjustment of the ordi\nnance committee shall hold hearings\non zone changes, and Mayor Quigley\nagreed that there was room for dis\npute as the ordinance stands. Alder\nman Johnson, chairman of the ordi\nnance committee, said he had in\ntended to have the matter attended\nto with the assistance of the corpor\nation counsel and he regretted that\nhe had not done so. It will be done,\nhowever, prior to the regular meet\ning next month, he said.\nAlderman Falk, commenting on\nthe quarterly report of Sealer of\nWeights and Measures Carl A. Carl\nson, expressed the opinion that\nsomething should be done to correct\nthe condition noted from time to\ntime in coal dealers' weights as re\ncorded by the sealer. Mayor Quigley\nreplied that the sealer has the power\nto prosecute dealers found giving\nshort weight. The sealer's report\nlisted 14 dealers, 13 of whom were\ngiving weights of between 5 and 110\npounds in excess of standard, and\none was 95 short.\nCouncilman Greene's petition to\nhave repairs made to the gutters on\nCommonwealth avenue between\nStanley and Carlton streets was re\nferred to the board of public works,\nas was Councilman Sablotsky's pe\ntion for repairs on Lyle road and\nPendleton road. 1\n-Councilman Scheuy petitioned for\nthe cleaning out and filling in of\ngutters on Griswold street between\nHart and Columbia streets and it\nwas referred to the board of public\nworks.\nCAPITOL\nTHEATER\nNew Britain\nMatinee Sat.\nNew York\nPlayers 4\nIn\nThe Happy Comedy\n\"Apron Strings\"-\nBeginning Monday, Oct. 20\nTHE GREAT DRAMA\nCoquette\nBuy Reserved Seats Ahead!\nGRAN0\nHARTFORD M\nNow!\nTWICE DAILY\nALL WEEK\nA Parisian Thrill!\n\"NIGHT LIFE\nIN PARIS\"\nFeaturing I Villa Maj-o\nNEXT WEEK 5-\n\"Peek-a-Boo\"\nThe Burlesque Riot!\nAlderman Falk petitioned for re\npairs at the corner of Cherry and\nWhiting streets and the matter was\nreferred to the board of public\nworks. Numerous other similar pe\ntitions were referred to the same\nboard.\nA-request was received for adop\ntion of a resolution adopted by the\ncity of Grand Rapids, Mich., and\ncalling on municipalities to join\nforces in a fight for the return of\nprosperity. On motion of Council\nman Conlon, it was ordered printed\nwithout reading and will be acted\nupon at the November meeting.\nColumbia Street Refund Discussed\nThe report of the mayor and\naldermen and the corporation coun\nsel was adopted as follows:\n\"In the matter of refund of sewer\nassessment paid by Arthur E. Mahon\nand wife, $80.50 on Lot No. 10, Co\nlumbia street, in May 11, 1929. re\nferred to the mayor and board of\naldermen and corporation counsel by\nthe common council at its August\nmeeting, 1930, we beg leave to re\nport that the city had a lien on the\npremises improved, which would\npersist for 60 days from the date of\nthe second notice by publication, and\ncould be continued thereafter by the\nfiling of a certificate in the office of\nthe town clerk.\n\"The city's lien was an encum\nbrance on petitioners' property, tak\ning precedence over all other en\ncumbrances, and the amount of the\nlien could have been collected by\nforeclosure proceedings. Petitioners,\nhowever, quite properly paid the\namount of the lien during the 60 day\nperiod, thus obviating the necessity\nof filing the lien certificate.\n\"The opinion of the corporation\ncounsel given in certain cases as to\ntho validity of liens for city im\nprovements was based solely on\nwhether the certificate of lien was\nfiled in proper time. The fact that\nproperty has changed ownership\nbefore the lien is filed does not in\nvalidate the city's right to collect the\nassessment out of the land benefited.\nIf this were not so the owner of the\nproperty at the time of the comple\ntion of the Improvement might, if\nso disposed, transfer his property,\nconceal and hide his attachable pro\nperty and thus leave the city with\nout redress. The charter gives the\nright to 'assess benefits upon the\nproper parties or lands especially\nbenefited by the proposed Improve\nment.' \"We therefore recommend that\nthe common council give the peti\ntioners leave to withdraw.\"\nOn recommendation of the claims\ncommittee and corporation counsel.\nIt was voted to pay Otto L. Vater of\nBassett street $200 in settlement of\nhis claim for compensation for in\njuries sustained in a fall on an alleg\ned icy sidewalk on Bassett street, in\nfront of the Erwin home in January.\nREV. DR. H. F. CASSIDY\nASSIGNED TO NORFOLK\nPastor of Church in Farmington\nGiven New Assignment By\nBishop Nilan\nHartford, Oct. 16 W) Among the\nchanges in clerical appointments by\nBishop Nilan announced in this\nweek's Catholic Transcript is that\nof the Rev. Henry F. Cassidy, LL.D,\nfrom the pastorate of Farmington\nto the pastorate of the Immaculate\nConception church, Norfolk.\nFather Cassidy was a chaplain of\na Connecticut regiment in the lato\nwar with Germany, and he has tak\nen a patriotic interest in the Ameri\ncan Legion of which he was chap\nlain. In his new pastorate at Norfolk.\nFather Cassidy succeeds Rev. Paul\nF. Keating.\nRev. James F. Barnett of the\nChurch of the Immaculate Concep\ntion church, Hartford, succeeds Dr.\nCassidy in the pastorate of St. Pat\nrick's church, Farmingtonv Rev.\nJames P. Jimmins has been trans\nferred from the chaplaincy of St.\nAgnes' home, West Hartford, to that\nof St. Joseph's Academy, West Hart\nford, and as administrator of St.\nMary's church, Newington.\nRev. Augustine J. Hennessy has\nbeen transferred from St. Patrick's\nchurch, East Hampton, to the chai\nlalncy of St. Agnes' home, West\nHartford.\nBAPTISTS TO MEET\nNew London, Oct. 16 (UP) Tho\nConnecticut Baptist convention was\nto open here today with a ministers'\nconference at 2 p. m.\nMrs. J. J. Allen, wife of the Rev.\nJ. J. Allen of the First Baptist\nchurch of this city, and Mrs. Ernest\nE. Rogers, wife of the lieutenant\ngovernor, were hostesses at an in\nformal reception at the church.\nIndia has a small fish, the gour\nami, which gives an audible croak\nwhen on the surface of the water.\nBENNY\nRUBIN\nALICE DAY\nA side splitting\ncomedy with Bis\nieague Love\nLaughter.\nI\nChallenges World\nSeries for Actiou\nand Thrills.\nADDED FEATURE\n\"TEMPLE TOWER\"\nBULLDOG DRUMMOND\" Back Again in\nA 1X3X MOVIETONE MELODRAMA\nwith H. B. Walthall and Star Cast\nDARING! SUSPENSE! ROMANCE!\nFOX SOUND NEWS\nE\nM\nComing Saturday\nJOE E. BROWN in \"MAYBE IT'S LOVE\"\nSucceeds in First Set\nOf A. M. A. Examination\nHAROLD SCHECHTMAX\nHarold Schechtman, son of Mrs.\nR. Schechtman of 431 Chestnut\nstreet this city, has been informed\nthat lie has successfully completed\nthe first set of national medical ex\naminations that were held at Wash\nington, D. C, this summer. These\nexaminations are given yearly by the\nnational board of the American\nMedical association and allow a\nperson receiving a diploma to prac\ntice medicine in any state of the\nunion without further examination.\nMr. Schechtman is a junior at the\nMedical college of the University of\nVermont. He has been a member\nof the varsity football team during\nhis academic years and past chancel\nlor of Tail Epsilon Phi fraternity.\nBoys on Inspection\nOf Brokerage Office\nBoys of the senior class of the\nstate trade school were escorted\nthrough the brokerage office of Put\nnam Co. yesterday afternoon by\nManager Earl F. Baker, and were\nshown the stock market mysteries.\nThe boys were given a practical\ndemonstration of a stock transac\ntion from the placing of an order\nby a customer and the execution of\nthe order in New York to the final\ndelivery of the certificate.\nMr. Baker explained, what takes\nplace when a customer \"sells short,\"\nexplained the operations of the\nticker and the quotations on the\nboard, and answered many ques\ntions for his guests.\nRETURNED TO REFORMATORY\nWillimantic. Oct. 16 (UP) Three\nProvidence. R. I., boys were re\nturned today to the state reforma\ntory from which they escaped last\nSaturday night.\nThe boys, Manuel Alvis. 16, Joseph\nLupo, 17, and Ernest Bernier, 17,\nwere found hiding in underbrush\nalong the Willimantic river last\nnight.\nAcute laryngitis caused the death\nof George Washington.\nToday and Tomorrow\nAmerica's Dancing Daughter\nJoan Crawford\nin\n'Our Blushing Brides'\nCo-Feature\nThe best laugh of the season\nJack Oakie in\n\"The Social Lion'\nSound News. Comedy. Novelties\nCOMING SOON\nThe most remarkable picture\never filmed\nWomen will love it\nMen will thrill to it!\nRecord Crowds Yesterday\nGo Wild Over Mighty\nTWO FEATURE SHOW\nHurry! Hurry! Ends Tomorrow!\nrVJtth\nand\n\nWarner Bros.\nsY\nUnless otherwise indicated, theatrical notices and reviews In this column uw\nwritten by press agencies for tbe respective amusement company.\nAT THE EMBASSY\nYesterday the large audiences\nroared for two hours and it's all due\nto Benny Rubin, the screen's funny\nman. He held the crowds in one\nround of riotous laughter after an\nother. The story is woven around\nthe world series baseball games in\nwhich Benny proves the hero of the\nworld's sport classic. He's simply\namusing an a fine cast that sur\nrounds him makes this feature one\nof the outstanding funny pictures\nof the year.\nPacked with thrills from first to\nlast and given a directorial and\nhotographic treatment that brings\nout its entertainment qualities to\nthe utmost, \"Temple Tower.\" which\nplays on the same program, will in\ntroduce New Britain screen fans to\nsomething new in the way of film\nfare.\nThe novel by H. C. McNeiie is the\nlatest and most successful of his\nseries on \"Bulldog Drummond,\" and\nwith Kenneth MacKenna in the role\nof the intrepid ex-officer. Director\nDonald Gallaher has produced a\ngripping and faithful all talking Fox\nMovietone version of the original\nstory.\n\"Temple Tower\" has as its theme\nthe theft of a priceless jewel col\nlection and the resultant double\ncrossing of two of the crooks by the\nother two, Blackton and his giant\naccomplice, Gaspard, who take the\nemeralds and mdefrom the wrath\nof the other couple behind the\nstrongly guarded walls of Temple\nTower, a gloomy mansion.\nThe maneuvers of the crooks at\ntract the attention of Drummond,\nwho begins an investigation which\nin turn leads him into one desperate\nsituation after another, especially\nwhen a mysterious girl enters the\naffair, hoping to save her from the\nMasked Strangler, the \"master\nmind\" criminal behind the whole\nplot.\nGRAND THEATER, HARTFORD\n\"Nite Life in Paris\" a pleasant\nsurprise for those who anticipate only\nanother show enters the last half o\nits engagement at the Hartford\nJaugh hub with performances today\nat the Grand theater with LaViila\nMaye and Charles (Tramp) McNally\nheading the battalions of fun this\nParisian offering has gone over big.\nNext week's attraction is announc\ned as being \"Peek-A-Boo\" a brand\nnew production making its first\nswing around the wheel this season.\nAccording to the advance dope\n\"Peek-A-Boo\" has new novelties that\nare certain to appeal to the.\" dis\ncriminating theatergoer. Hal Rath\nbun boob comic and Erin Jackson\nsoubrette are featured in a cast that\nsparkles with burlesque and vaude\nville celebrities.\nFind Unidentified Body\nIn River in Stratford\nBridgeport, Oct. 16 UP) Police to\nday were seeking to establish the\nidentity of the body of a man found\nin a swamp in the Farmill river\ndistrict of Stratford yesterday by\nduck hunters.\nThere were no indications of foul\nplay on the body which police be\nlieve had been in the water for a\nyear and a half. It is believed the\nman wandered into the swamp and\nwas drowned.\nWarner Bros.\nTODAY, FRI., SAT.\nWould you keep your\nmouth shut if you saw\na daring Northern gun\nman kill a man? Would\nyou fight for the pret\ntiest girl in the snow\nlands even if that same\nbad man wanted this\nmiss? It's red bloodril\nadventure in the w\nnorth woods.\nA Great Cast\nGeorge O'Brien\nHelen Chandler\nAntonio Moreno\nNoel Frances\nComing\n\"A LADY\n1 StranD mf\ntftfbw Don't Miss j\nln 1 Tomorrow U\nI CABARET g\nNIGHT j\nT os THK STAGE U C\nD V AUDEVILLti D\nACTS ACTS\nFeaturing\n1 The BROWN DERBY BAND\n10 people 10 Don't Miss\nTomorrow\nJack McBride in 'What Next' Tomorrow\nCABARET CABARET\nChisholm Brecn NIGHT\nNIGHT\nClad Moffat The Tappers 3 Loads of fun\nI1\" J-\nAT THE STRAND\nA new kind of \"party\" comes to\nthe screen in \"Rough- Romance,\"\nFox Movietone all talking drama of\nthe great outdoors now playing\nwith five acts of vaudeville at tho\nStrand.\nThe films which have depicted\n\"wild\" parties, tea parties, block\nffarties, yachting parties in fact,\nalmost every conceivable form of\nparty had never, heretofore, pre\nsented what is undoubtedly one of\nthe roughest, most hilarious forms\nof \"party\" a logging town \"jam\nboree!\" The \"jamboree.\" according to\nthose fortunate enough to witness\nits filming, is a sort of cross be\ntween a crowd of cowboys whoop\ning it up in Red Gulch and the bat\ntle of the Marne.\n\"Rough Romance,\" which was di\nrected by A. F. Erickson, features\nGeorge O'Brien, Helen Chandler.\nAntonio Moreno and Noel Francis.\nWith this magnificent picture the\nStrand presents on the stage five\nacts of vaudeville featuring the\nBrown.Derby band with Frank and\nMilt Britton and their exponents of\nintellectual insanity that have been\nheadlining in all the leading vaude\nville theaters throughout the coun\ntry. The voice of the people has re\ncently called loud and long for an\norchestra with soloists. Frank and\nMilt Britton will supply the music\nspecialties. The Tappers Three will\nTap, Tap. Tap. Jack McBride. that\nfunny boy in \"What Next,\" a laugh\nevery second while he is on the\nstage. Chisholm Breen, another\nlaughable skit in a comedy of the\nnow country. Then Glad Mofntt, a\nsinger of glad songs. Fo rtomorrow\nevening you will w itness another of\nthe Cabaret Nights.\nAT THE CAPITOL\nThe final performances of \"Apron\nStrings\" by the New York Players\nwill be on Saturday, with a matinee\nat 2:15. The Capitol theater has\nbeen the scene this week of a happy\nreunion of old time theater goers\nwho have missed the spoken drama\nfrom the local stage these many\nyears. Its return, as Mayor Quigley\nsaid on the Capitol stage on Mon\nday night, has been auspicious in the\ncapable hands of the New York\nPlayers. Each performance has seen\nincreasing attendance, and patrons\nare now urged to buy their seats in\nadvance and avoid waiting in line at\nthe box office. Seats are on sale this\nweek and next.\nBeginning Monday evening an en\ntirely different form of play will be\npresented by the Players. The muse\nwill turn from comedy to trenchant\ndrama. \"Coquette\" will be the sec\nond week's offering. It is a drama\nwith a \"kick\" and has a beautiful\nappeal. No lover of the spoken\ndrama should miss \"Coquette.\" It is\na truly American in authorship, in\nlocale and in character drawing. Re\nserved seats are selling for all next\nweek, and reservations should be\nmade in advance.\nNEW LONDON JOB LET\nWashington, Oct. 16 OP) A con\ntract was awarded by the navy to\nday to the Newport Contracting and\nEngineering Company, Inc., Lee\nHall. Virginia, to rebuild the piers\nat the submarine base. New London,\nConnecticut, for $114,496.\nSUNDAY\nSURRENDERS\"\nWORCESTER CRASH\nTAKESTWO LIVES\nAuto Leaves Road-Harvard\nProfessor and Wife Die\nWorcester, Mass., Oct. 16 (UP)\nProfessor Ernest Henry Wilson of\nHarvard University, widely known\nbotanist and explorer, and his wife\nwere killed yesterday when their\nautomobile skidded on wet leaves\non the Boston Pet road, crashed\nthrough an iron fence, and dropped\n0 feet over a steep embankment.\nMrs. Wilson, who was diving, was\nkilled instantly, and her husband\ndied soon after arrival at the Wor\ncester City hospital. A pet dog was\nsy seriously injured it had to be\nshot.\nProfessor Wilson was assistant di\nrector of the Arnold Arboretum,\nHarvard's famous botanical garden\nin Boston. In collecting plant life\nin the Far East for the arboretum\nh(; became internationally famous\namong botanists and explorers. The\nRoyal Horticultural Society of Great\nBritain recognized his work in 19 26\nby bestowing on him the Veitch\nmemorial medal, the first time the\nhonor had been accorded an Ameri\ncan. He was also the first person\noutside the British Isle to receive\nthe Victoria medal of honor from\nthe Royal Horticultural Society.\nMrs. Roscoe Arbuckle\nGiven Divorce Decree\nLos Angeles, Oct. H (UP) Ros\ncoe \"Fatty\" Arbuckle, once famous\nas the screen's heaviest comedian.\nwas single again today as the re\nsult of a superior court order grant\ning a final decree of divorce to\nDoris Deane Arbuckle. film actress\nFriends said that Miss Deane.\nwho married Arbuckle in 1925 and\nleft him three years later, intended\nto marry Allan S. Lund, oLs An\nChildren say great\nYou can eat Shredded Wheat Biscuit\nright out of the package with milk or\ncream but it tastes better if you\ncrisp the biscuits in the oven and pour\nhot milk over them. The flavory\nshreds of baked wheat are so crisp\nand delicious children always ask\nfor more and it is so good for them;\nContains everything their growing\nbodies need. Delicious with fruits.\nSKDDE\nAIM\nSEE A WIFE'S SIDE\nOf This Shocking Question\n\"A LADY\nSurrenders\"\nIs It Fair For a Man to Cheat If\nTrapped Into a Loveless, Selfish Marriage?\n6\n4\nDAYS\nBEGINNING\nSUNDAY\nS WARNER BROS. Ba.\ntranD\nNEW RRITAIN\ngeles attorney. The actress refused\nto confirm the rumor.\nLund represented her In obtain\nlng her divorce.\nFOUR AUTO CRASH\nDEATHSJN STATE\nThree Persons Killed Yesterday,\nOne Dies ol Injuries\nNew Haven, Oct. IS P) Three\npersons were killed in automobile\naccidents in Connecticut yesterday\nand a fourth died of injurlei suffer\ned in an automobile crash last\nSaturday.\nMrs. Julia Cronshaw, 35, of New\nYork city, who had been attending\nthe wedding of her brother, Law\nrence Hajas of Fairfield, was fatally\ninjured when a machine driven by\nanother brother, Eugene Haja of\nFairfield, skidded on the wet pave\nment and turned over in a field at\nGreens Farms. Three other persona\nIncluding Mrs. Cronshaw's husband\nand her 11 year old son, were Beri\nously injured.\nIn Rockville John Brill, J5, died\nseveral hours after he had been\nstruck by a truck driven by Edard\nMohr of Manchester. The latter was\nnot held.\nAn unidentified man about SO\nyears old was killed In South Wind\nsor by an auto driven by Frank Mc\nDonald of Hamden, who said he\nthought the man had staggered\nagainst his machine. A, bottle of\nliquor was found in the victim'\nclothing.\nMrs. Joseph Walker, Sr., of Perth\nAmboy, N. J., died in Norwalk from\ninjuries suffered Saturday when a\ncar operated by her daughter-in-law\nMrs. Lois Lefler Walker of West\nport crashed into a tree at Westport.\nForeign workers, including1- Bel\ngians, Poles, and Italians, to the\nnumber of about 200,000 have been\nimported into France since the war.\n9\nDEO\nEAT\nvim\nWITH ALL THE BRAN\nOF THE WHOLEWHEAT\n4\nDAYS\nBEGINNING\nSUNDAY","height":"25712","width":"19140"}}
